article.headline: Bucks lose in Phoenix for 17th straight time
article.linkText: Balanced Suns win sixth in a rowl
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix Suns lead the league in scoring and are showing no signs of slowing down. Shawn Marion and Steve Nash had double-doubles, leading four teammates in double-digit scoring, and the Suns won their sixth straight game by beating the Milwaukee Bucks 111-104 Wednesday night. Marion had 23 points and 12 rebounds and Nash had 22 points and 12 assists. "It's a lot of fun playing with so many terrific offensive players," Nash said. "In some ways it's difficult, because you want to make sure everyone gets the ball, their touches, and it's difficult to do, but at the same time it's a lot of fun because they're so talented." Quentin Richardson had 20 points, Amare Stoudemire 16, Joe Johnson 13 and Leandro Barbosa, Nash's backup, had a season-high 12. The Suns have defeated Milwaukee 17 consecutive times in Phoenix. The Suns (10-2) are off to the second-best start in franchise history, behind the 14-2 start in 1980-81. "We're playing team basketball right now, and that's what it's about," Stoudemire said. "We're playing defense, running, scoring and playing real good." Michael Redd had 22 points and 10 rebounds for the Bucks, who dropped their sixth in a row and fell to 0-6 on the road, and Desmond Mason had 20 points and 10 rebounds. Joe Smith had nine of his season-high 18 points off the bench in the fourth quarter, and Erick Strickland also had a season-high with 14. "They have a lot of firepower over there, but once again it has been the same story throughout the course of this four-game road trip," Mason said. "After three quarters we are right in the game, and then in the fourth quarter we can't hit the big shots." The Suns, who had an historic collapse when they blew a 19-point lead in the last quarter at Cleveland on Nov. 10, wore the Bucks out in typical surge-and-splurge style. Milwaukee led only once -- in the opening minute -- but got within three points with 6:47 left before the Suns pulled away. The Bucks began a 15-3 run late in the third quarter and pulled to 91-88 in the fourth after a three-point play by Redd, a 3-pointer by Mike James and layups by Mason and Smith in quick succession. Nash gave Phoenix breathing room when he anticipated James' behind-the-back, crosscourt pass, knifed through for a steal and made a layup at the other end for a 93-88 lead. He also figured in a clutch play with a half-court, alley-oop pass to Marion for a layup with 3:35. That sent Phoenix ahead, 101-92, and Nash made it 103-92 with a fast-break layup 43 seconds later. The point guard had several unorthodox assists, including one between Milwaukee center Dan Gadzuric's legs to Stoudemire for an easy dunk in the third quarter. "That's the playground move that all of us wanted to do in the schoolyard and we usually get slapped for it," Suns coach Mike D'Antoni said. "Steve just, you know, that's a heck of a line for 31 minutes, and then Leandro had his best game. Everybody contributed -- it's another 111 points against a team that's dangerous." Phoenix had double-digit leads in each of the first two quarters, but let the Bucks tighten the game each time. In the third, the Suns pulled away from a 61-60 lead with 9:54 to play to go up 88-73 with 47 seconds left in the quarter on Johnson's 17-foot jumper. Nash had six assists and eight points in the quarter The Suns had a 13-point lead after a layup by Nash with 4:37 left in the first, but Milwaukee tied it at 30 with an 18-5 run capped by Strickland's jumper with 22 seconds left. Then the Bucks, who shot 64 percent in the first quarter, missed nine of their first 10 shots in the second, and Barbosa had 11 points during a surge that carried Phoenix to a 49-34 lead with 6:47 remaining. "This is not an easy team to play at the end of a back-to-back," Bucks coach Terry Porter said. "I feel our guys did a great job of coming in and competing."

Game notes
The Suns have won 24 of 27 games with Milwaukee. The Bucks are 0-12 in America West Arena. ... Stoudemire and Nash entered the game ranked 1-2 in NBA field-goal accuracy at 59.3 and 57.1 percent, respectively. Stoudemire was 5-of-15, but Nash went 11-of-16. ... Redd, an All-Star guard, was back in form after scoring a season-low six points against the Lakers in Los Angeles the night before.
